<HEAD>Will Saving Rare Bird Cost Timber Jobs in South?</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY301,302 of May 16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALLAHAN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Timber man Jim Coleman's boot makes the
same print in the forest floor as biologist Ralph Costa's, and both
men call themselves environmentalists.
   The similarities end when they talk about a humble little bird
called the red-cockaded woodpecker and the complex new rules to
preserve a million acres of Southern pine woods for the endangered
creature's home.
   Three logging contracts signed by Coleman's small company were
scrapped when the U.S. Forest Service regulations changed to give
the bird more space, and he sees layoffs looming in the region's
biggest industry.
   ``If we were out there destroying the environment, that'd be one
thing,'' says Coleman, whose Callahan Timber Co. planted more than
1 million seedlings last year. ``We're at a loss. We don't
understand.''
   Costa, who oversees a program to save the woodpecker in the
Appalachicola National Forest 200 miles away, says timber interests
alone must not drive decisions about federal woodlands.
   ``Public lands are going to be the last places that things
survive, pieces of the world _ whether it's a woodpecker or a bald
eagle,'' he said. ``They're the bastions.''
   Disagreement about the red-cockaded woodpecker has generated
legal briefs and government studies that now stack up well over the
bird's seven-inch height.
   The species, named for the tiny badges of red plumage behind the
male's eyes, has been on the endangered list since 1970.
   Perhaps 10,000 birds remain, the rest falling prey to flying
squirrels, snakes and even other woodpeckers that take over the
cavities they painstakingly dig in living pine trees.
   Man, often unwittingly, has been the birds' adversary, too,
consuming much of their habitat _ parklike stands of old pines to
nest in and enough surrounding woods to forage for insects, find
mates and expand their clans.
   As the Sun Belt's population has grown, developers have turned
woods into housing tracts. Loggers have replaced swaths of old
forest with tree crops, raised and cut in cycles.
   And the government routinely has extinguished the fires caused
by lightning that actually helped the woodpecker by burning out
hardwoods that spring up beneath tall pines, blocking nest cavities
and giving predators easier access.
   ``By far the largest factor has been clearcutting, destruction
of the habitat and suppression of fire,'' says Doug Honnold of the
Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund.
   The group accused the Forest Service in a lawsuit of
jeopardizing the species in Texas, and in 1988, a judge agreed,
banning clearcutting and other timber industry methods within
three-quarters of a mile of woodpecker colony sites. The case is on
appeal.
   After a similar suit was threatened concerning national forests
in eight other Southern states, the agency last year applied a
three-quarter-mile protection zone to those areas, too.
   It then was the timber industry's turn to sue, citing the Forest
Service's historic mandate ``to furnish a continuous supply of
timber.''
   It also contended the agency had failed to fully implement
earlier, less restrictive guidelines for the bird, and hadn't
followed required procedures in changing the rules.
   ``Unfortunately, we're fighting procedure versus emotion,'' says
Deborah Baker of the Atlanta-based industry group that filed suit,
the Forest Service Timber Purchasers Council.
   The three-quarter-mile radius encompasses 1,100 acres. That's
1.2 million acres for all the known colonies, compared with 502,000
restricted acres under the previous rules, which set only a
half-mile zone, according to the American Forest Council in
Washington.
   Ron Escano, the Forest Service official in charge of protecting
endangered species in the Southeast, says the acreage was added to
give the birds space to expand colonies, not merely maintain
existing ones. In all but three national forests that have the
woodpeckers, the population seemed to be declining under the old
rules, he says.
   The new rules are interim measures while a two-year
environmental impact assessment is completed, he says.
   Meanwhile, Escano insists, timber cutting can occur within the
current zones _ ``it's just that it has to be designed to benefit
the woodpecker.''
   Asked about the industry's complaint that the new rules reduced
timber harvests by a total of 73 million board feet this year and
last, Escano says, ``In relation to total volume cut ... it's quite
small.''
   He acknowledges, however, ``If you look at individual forests
and individual operators, it could be a very different story.''
   According to Michael Sparks, a Forest Service timber sales
official, the impact will be greatest in coastal areas from East
Texas to North Carolina.
   In fiscal 1989, about 1.2 billion board feet of timber was cut
on Southeast national forests, a drop from the previous five years.
The value fell to $76.8 million after hovering around $100 million
annually through that period.
   Woodpecker protection is certainly not the only factor
influencing volume, but the new guidelines are being felt.
   Jim Coleman doesn't know how much it cost Callahan Timber when
three contracts for northern Florida's Osceola National Forest were
canceled and then renegotiated because of the rule change.
   ``It's really hurt the industry down here,'' he says. ``When you
pull timber off the market, then this timber has to be found
somewhere _ and if it can't be found, then these mills start
shutting down.''
   One mill he's thinking of is a utility-pole operation owned
jointly by Callahan Timber and Richard Cochran.
   Cochran echoes a complaint often heard in timbering areas, that
the bird is really a surrogate, ``a tool ... for people who just
don't want to cut any timber.''
   ``If we could reason with each other, we should have enough
middle ground,'' he says.
   ``No, the time for compromise is over,'' says Gary Henry, who
oversees red-cockaded woodpecker preservation for the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service. ``That's what's been occurring for years ...
hoping that this was adequate for the woodpecker. It's very obvious
today that it is not adequate.''
   Couldn't the industry simply turn to private lands for raw
material?
   There are 164 million acres of private timberland in the
Southeast, many times the total national forest acreage, according
to the American Forest Council. But much private land is less
carefully managed and quality is often lower, industry officials
say.
   Ralph Costa drives past miles of private timberlands, paper
company plantations, on his commute to work in the Appalachicola
National Forest, home to 1,000 or so of the woodpeckers, more than
anywhere else. It doesn't bother him to see trees cut on private
land.
   But, he says, ``I don't think that national forests or any
public lands, for that matter, should necessarily have an objective
of producing a cash crop.''
   Deer hunting is permitted to thin herds. ``Cutting a tree ought
to be the same way. We ought to take trees for the health of the
ecosystem,'' says Costa, who's often in the woods before dawn to
band red-cockadeds or move birds from his forest to others,
sometimes providing mates in colonies that have dwindled to a
single bird.
   ``People ask me what's the value of a woodpecker,'' Costa says,
answering with an analogy: ``You can take a nice fancy spider web
and start cutting the threads. You're going to clip one thread
eventually and the spider web is going to collapse.
   ``And we can keep throwing species off the planet, which we're
doing, and eventually something's going to go wrong.''
</TEXT>
