<LEADPARA>  THREE new homes for the poor aren't going to dent any community's housing
problems. But when they're built in Alviso by Habitat for Humanity, cheers are
in order and lessons abound.;    Last June, some 50 families were evicted from
their shacks at the southern end of San Francisco Bay when the landlord
decided his land could earn money another way. The evictions were legal, but
they were quick and crude.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HABITAT-FORMING
THE ALVISO HOMES SHOW THE BEST OF NON-PROFIT
HOUSING DEVELOPERS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Editorials  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Most of the 300 displaced people simply left the area. Others stayed in
shelters for the homeless. Eventually seven remaining families and the Bay &amp;
Valley Habitat for Humanity found each other.;    For 15 years, non-profit
Habitat organizations across the United States have been recruiting skilled
volunteers, wangling land from cities and low-interest loans from lenders to
build thousands of homes. The families who move in almost always help build
the homes.;    Habitat's success in Alviso underscores the vitality and
commitment of non-profit developers. It also should shame a federal government
that continues its 1980s retreat from low-cost housing.;    Yet there's much
that government, labor and business can do to help the non-profits help the
poor.;    Local and federal officials can streamline the red tape that can
slow or stymie non-profit projects. Tax credits for low-income housing, so
popular among investors because of their socially redeeming value, could be
increased to pre-1986 tax reform levels. Construction trade unions could lower
pay scales for non-profit developments. Suppliers could offer more discounts.
Employers could excuse more volunteers from their regular jobs.;    Meanwhile,
three Alviso families and Habitat for Housing have demonstrated to Santa Clara
County the potential and benefits of non-profit housing. And four more homes
are in the works.  </TEXT>
