<HEAD>Non-Profit Housing Group Launches Its Largest Project Yet</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 construction volunteers, led in a
rousing hymn by Mayor Andrew Young, began work Monday to build 20
homes in five days for working but poor families.
   The effort by the non-profit Habitat for Humanity, an ecumenical
Christian organization, is named the ``Jimmy Carter Work Project''
in honor of the former president, a former Habitat board member who
will join the workers for the final three days. It is the group's
largest project yet.
   Young, also a Congregationist minister, proclaimed it ``Habitat
for Humanity Week'' and led the crew in an impromptu rendition of
``When The Roll Is Called Up Yonder.''
   ``You bring with you the spirit and love of God, and a concern
for `the least of these' _ God's children,'' Young told the
workers. ``We are willing to combine our service and our cash in
the service of Christ.''
   The three-bedroom, one-bath houses being constructed in the
Edgewood neighborhood will be sold at no profit, with no interest,
to 20 working families with children. Mortgage payments will
average about $175 a month, including taxes and insurance.
   The new neighborhood is being built on a block of land in
southeast Atlanta donated by the city. Supporting the 400-odd
construction workers are another 800 volunteers handling a variety
of chores.
   Plans call for 30 more houses to be built in the Cabbagetown
neighborhood by 1989 and 25 more homes by 1990 in another
neighborhood. Habitat for Humanity is working to raise $1.5 million
for the first 50 homes in the Atlanta project.
   Young recalled that he and his wife, Jean, were able to buy a
home of their own years ago, when he worked on a small salary at
the Southern Christian Leadership Conference and she earned even
less as a teacher.
   ``Now ... it's almost impossible to afford the home, the
financing and the interest,'' he said, adding that ``never before
in the history of this country have we had such a crisis in
housing.''
   But through Habitat for Humanity, ``we can have homes with no
profit, and no interest,'' Young said.
   The effort is ``real rewarding work,'' said project director
Bruce Gunter, an Atlanta investments counselor and veteran Habitat
volunteer. ``This is such a motivational bunch of folks.''
   About one-third of this week's workers are in the construction
business themselves, Gunter said. ``Another third are moderately
skilled, and the other third don't know one end of the hammer from
the other.
   ``But there's work for everybody; you need some people to tote
things, too,'' he said.
   Also on Monday, Habitat for Humanity supporters began a
1,200-mile walk from Portland, Maine, to Georgia. Along the way,
they plan to build 120 homes for needy families.
   Sunday in Macon, about 200 people walked a mile in 100-degree
heat to the first house built by Habitat in that central Georgia
city.
   Habitat for Humanity was founded in 1976 by Millard Fuller, a
millionaire businessman who, in the late 1960s, gave away his
fortune and began working to house the poor.
   Carter served on Habitat's board from 1984-87 and continues to
work with the organization.
</TEXT>
