<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / UK Company News: Second half boost for Storehouse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN FOOTBALL parlance, it was a game of two halves at Storehouse last year.
After a pretty dismal first six months in which it lost Pounds 13.9m, the
retailing group, which includes BhS, Mothercare, Habitat, Richards and
Blazer, recorded a strong improvement in the second half with trading
profits for the period bouncing to Pounds 27.3m compared with Pounds 13.2m
the year before. Over the same period sales grew from Pounds 572m to Pounds
606.4m.
At the heart of Storehouse's turnround was a strong recovery from BhS, the
clothing and homeware group, which has undergone something of a
metamorphosis under the direction of its chief executive, Mr David Dworkin -
who it was announced yesterday would replace Mr Michael Julien as group
chief executive.
BhS contributed Pounds 22.1m (Pounds 21.6m) to full year trading profits and
Pounds 634.7m (Pounds 617.7m) to sales. But Mr Dworkin believes there are
further significant benefits to be reaped from BhS. 'My own view is that the
month we are in is the best we have ever had. Last year we had our 'May
mania' when everything that was not tied down was on sale. But even so we
are beating the living hell out of those numbers this year,' he said.
However, it was not the same story across the group. Although Storehouse
said the sales trend had improved since Christmas, the Mothercare
childrenswear business experienced a sharp fall into a Pounds 3.9m loss for
the year reversing a previous profit of Pounds 6.8m. This decline was blamed
on increased costs and intensified competition. Sales were slightly down at
Pounds 233.8m (Pounds 234.8m).
Habitat, the furniture group, also had a tough year recording losses of
Pounds 8.8m against Pounds 11.9m. Its French arm made a strong contribution,
but the UK was weak and Conran's Habitat in the US lost Pounds 7.7m although
remedial action was promised this year. Habitat's sales also fell marginally
to Pounds 201.2m (Pounds 205.9m).
The Richards womenswear chain recorded a small increase in operating profits
but Blazer made a small loss. Together, they accounted for Pounds 600,000
(Pounds 1.7m) of profits and Pounds 110.1m (Pounds 103.2m) of sales.
Staff numbers were cut by about 500 to 14,260 during the year.
Storehouse devoted Pounds 45m to capital expenditure but is stepping up its
investment programme this year to more than Pounds 60m.
</TEXT>
